segments.text: We'll just talk about it because it's... Somebody, who was it?
The University Archives came to me about three or four years ago.
And a bunch of what you've asked is... You've got it.
Well, let me go get that tape.
I didn't realize that.
Okay, Charles Schulz or Dave Chapman.
Well, I forgot now, but I'm going to copy it and give it to you.
All right.
One thing you mentioned there about practice, there is an effort, at least, to say that every veterinarian practices his profession.
Now, there are those who say that, well, practice is private clinical practice.
Well, there is private clinical practice, but there's more practice than that.
I practice my profession in academia.
Good.
That's a good point.
Because I was defining practice as being in the business of veterinary medicine, the private enterprise.
Most people do.
And then they say, well, you other guys are not practicing.
We feel like we're practicing.
Well, that's a good point.
That will help me relieve some of the tensions I see between the two areas.
So we're all on the same plot there and all seeking to do the same thing.
And that is, the end result is,
a service to the people that they can't do themselves for a fee.
Now, we don't charge a fee, but we get people who can charge a fee, see, when they're out in private practice.
We're not private clinical practitioners.
Not even our veterinary hospital here is not private.
It's a public entity.
So it's not private, but it's practice, nevertheless.
Well, anyway, let's go back to the front.
Are you a Texan?
Yeah.
Born and reared in Erath County, Texas.
Yeah.
I was born to a farm family.
My daddy was a farmer.
He was a Sandyland peanut farmer.
He also later got into the beef cattle business and was a beef cattle producer.
My grandfather, he got into it because of my grandfather.
My mother's father, not his own.
His only father died before I was ever born.
But my mother's daddy was in the beef cattle business and bred and sold old her for cattle.
And he wasn't in the slaughter grade kind of production.
But he sold bulls to all over the country.
When did he get into that?
Ooh.
I don't know.
Can't tell you.
The year or anything like that.
In the 20s or 30s?
No, it's early.
Is that right?
The reason I ask, I have an uncle who was in Louisiana, but he was in the purebred hereford business.
And it was apparently, even in the 40s and,
or so, 30s, I guess, when he got into it.
It was a novel kind of thing.
There wasn't much of a chemistry.
Well, of course, my grandfather on the other side, we had the old Herford's who came to Texas from supposedly Mississippi.
And he never would reveal where he came from specifically and never would reveal any of his kinfolks.
We wonder if he had to skip country or something like that, you know?
He had an expression in Louisiana, going to Texas.
It meant something.
Anyway, he couldn't read and write.
He couldn't even count.
One, two, three, four, like that.
But he died.
He had 33,000 acres of land and a whole bunch of perfect cattle.
And did pretty well, but he came to Texas and Denton County and he went to work for an old fella that lived there in Denton County on a little farm, just day labor.
And he did it with a pretty good hand and his employer then decided to, you know, he'd rent to him on the haves.
He'd furnish all the mules and everything.
hornets and the plows and the seed and they'd split the profits at the end.
And then he did that for a while and decided he wanted to go three-fourths and so he got his own mules and farmed the land.
And then the next step was he bought the land right out of scratch.
And from there he got on up into the cattle business.
Well, anyway.
My daddy got into the beef cattle business because of my mother's father, really.
But principally, he was a farmer.
Well, having grown up there in Erath County and Sandeman, there wasn't anything there for me when I graduated from high school.
So I went to the oil field in Fort Worth, Texas.
Do you remember what year was that?
That was 1935.
And from there, well, in there I worked in the Alamo refinery, what was then called Wittenberg.
And it later changed to Phillips, but it's a little subdivision outside of the border of Texas.
I worked in the Alamo refinery, the gasoline refinery there.
And I was in with some guys that were 30 years old, and I was 17 years old, right off the farm.
Green is gold, you know.
And those guys had been working in the oil field for a long time.
They knew how to play all night from the foreman, you know, all that stuff.
And they treated me like I was their son, I guess.

The great guys, you know, they were giving me the shirt off their back, but they were vile, and they were vulgar, and their language was terrible, and they were always kidding with me, you know, and sending me over to get something that didn't even exist or something, you know, just pranks.
Well, I liked those guys, but at the end of the year, I thought, well, there's got to be something better than this.
So I quit, and I came back home to Erath County.
And thinking about going to college, I thought about several universities and colleges.
I decided I was a Baptist and my family was a Baptist.
I went over to Baylor, I guess.
I went over to Baylor University.
Got a job.
Had to have a job where I couldn't go.
So I got a job sweeping sidewalks to begin with.
Went back home and told Dad about it.
He said, well, Al, I just, you know, I'm concerned about it.
I'm afraid you're going to get over there and get started, and then the money's going to run out, and you just can't finish.
This was before I went to the oil field.
I got to the oil field.
This was before the oil field.
And he said, he's just afraid that I couldn't make it.
And that night, I thought, well, you know, Dad's pretty smart, and I am.
Maybe he's right.
So I went back to Waco and told him I wasn't coming.
Went on back home, and then I went to the oil field, Porter, Texas, and then had that experience there.
Well, when I came back home that time, then Dad was in no position to help me.
It was right after we began to come out of the Great Depression, and he just didn't have it.
scratching out of living there in that little sand hill in the farm.
So he said, well, let's go over to Deion and see if I can mortgage a heifer or something and get you a little money to go.
We went over to Deion.
We borrowed $25 to mortgage the old heifer.
He gave me that $25, and I went to talk to him.
Then we had the new deal.
$25 is what I had to have to pay down.
And I could pay the rest out over a period of time.
So I had to have a job again.
And a guy came along that was a, I guess you'd call him the garbage collector.
He was going around town picking up garbage.
And out at the edge of town he had a hog farm.
And he'd take my garbage out to feed his hogs.
So he gave me a job.
And that's what I did, was go around and pick up that garbage and go out and feed the hogs.
And that way, I was able to make enough to make it through Tarleton.
Finished Tarleton in a couple of years.
It was a junior college then.
And then I wanted to come to Texas.
So I talked to Dad again.
I paid all my debts there, but I didn't have enough money to cover debts.
My dad said, well, let's go back to the bank.
And we went back to the bank, and we parted $50.
And I stood at the edge of Stephenville, Texas, and put a ride down on a flatbed truck.
The guy that was going to Houston threw my luggage on the back end of that truck, and here we went.
I sat back there, and the wind was blowing, and I was nearly blowing off of that.
He stopped at the East Gate over there, and I got off with my luggage, and I started walking up to the big old pillars there.
And I said, an old country boy like me can't do this.
I turned around, and I started back.
down to Texas Avenue, to get you right back home.
I can't do that.
Then I said to myself, you idiot.
You're an idiot, just a plain idiot.
So I turned around and went on back up there.
Well, fortunately, at Tarleton, there was a veterinarian that taught me dairy science at Tarleton, a portion of dairy science.
His name was Vern Scott.
There is a Vern Scott Jr. today practicing there.
This is Vern Scott Sr. and he's deceased.
He was our veterinarian out on the ranching industry that Dad had, small but little.
And I'd watched him, you know, come out there.
He'd come out there and do some work.
He interested me very much, and I guess he is really the source of my interest in veterinary medicine.
Because usually there is someone like that.
I was going to ask you if you've been a county agent or a vocational ag teacher or what, but it was this guy.
Yeah, Dr. Vern Scott.
And he knew Dr. C.N.
Shepardson, Mr. C.N.
Shepardson it was, who used to be dean of agriculture here.
Before that, he was head of the Department of Dairy Science.
Yeah.
And he and Vern Scott had a relationship.
And Vern Scott told me that when you get down there, if you have any problems or anything like that or you need some help or something, you go over to see Mr. Shepherds and just tell him what it is.
And he's a guy that'll help you.
Well, I want to study veterinary medicine.
He was over in dairy science.
So I went to the College of Veterinary Medicine
the then dean of veterinary medicine, what was his name?
Oh, Dr. Maff, no one.
The second dean.
Marsteller.
Marsteller, yeah, Marsteller, of course.
I don't know why.
Yeah, me too, I went blank.
Marsteller was dean there, and I went over to Dr. Marsteller and told him I wanted to study veterinary medicine, and he said, well, fine.
And I said, well, we've got to have a job.
He said, well, that may be a problem.
He said, it's getting a little late in the summer, and all the jobs we're going to have for students have already been committed for this fall.
And I just don't, just can't give you any more.
And I, oh, I may have to go back home.
But I remembered what Dr. Vern Scott told me.
Go over and see Mr. Shepard's.
So I ambled over to Mr. Shepardson's office over in that agricultural building, still standing there.
And his office was in there.
And told him who I was.
And that Colonel Scott told me to come see him.
He agreed with me and said, well, yeah, I think we can get you a job down on the dairy farm.
We'll find one.
Now, you'd have to be a dairy science major, however,
and can't work over there.
Well, I want to study veterinary medicine, but I couldn't do that, and I couldn't without a job.
Well, maybe I better go the other way.
At least I'll be in college.
So I went over.
I told him, I'll take it.
And so he did, and I cleaned the barn, milked cows, and mowed grass for 25 cents an hour over there in dairy science.
I graduated from dairy science in 1940.
I had every intention of going into, going to work somewhere, I wasn't sure what, with a B.S.
degree and trying to save enough money to come back to veterinary medicine.
So... What kind of job opportunities were there then for B.S.
in animal science?
Pretty good?
Yeah, I think so.
I got a job before the summer was out.
Graduated in May of 40, and before the summer was out, I had a job.
There was a guy in Dairy Science, however, who coached the judging team.
That's all right.
But anyway, he got me a job in Lockhart, Texas on the Rock and Berry farm down there.
The guy with the name of Wilson managed it.
We had 600 cows.
And most of the milk went to Austin.
Anyway, I went down there and started working the fall of

Well late summer of 1940 and then of course stayed there until World War II broke out and I'd been through the Corps of Cadets and the Reserve Officer and when World War II broke out of course I got called in right away and didn't get back in that three year span that I had intended but in the meantime the war went on, spent four little four years there
And in the meantime, had married.
And by the time I got back to the States, I'd saved enough money to come to College of Veterinary Medicine.
So in 1946, then, I came back to study veterinary medicine and graduated in 1949.
Well, you were also in the GI Bill.
Yeah.
Yeah, that's right.
Did you run into a guy named Ray Hargis while you were a student?
Yeah, sure.
Ray's my cousin.
Is that right?
Yeah, he'd been shot down in Germany in 41 or 42, spent three years in prison and came back over here.
Yeah, you bet.
That's interesting.
You bet.
So you came back in 46 and then finished your degree in 49.
Came back in February of 46.
Was the demand for it, was it tough to get into the school at that time?
Do you remember?
In terms of numbers or?
Well, the numbers weren't as fast as they are today.
They had some more variation.
But my class started with, well, I'm almost afraid to tell you the exact numbers now.
That's all right.
I was wondering because it's so competitive now to get in there.
We lost a bunch.
More had that classroom failed out.
That started when I started.
We graduated on 44 students.
I think it was 72 students that started.
That sounds about right.
I seem like I've seen that number, that camera number as well.
At that time, what did most of the students, the veterinary students, anticipate going into upon graduation?
Private clinical practice.
In the private clinical practice.
In the country, rural settings, cattle business, everything?
Large animals.
Large animals.
Okay.
I'm going to follow that a little bit with you later.
Yeah, that was what I had my practice place picked out before I graduated.
You were as good.
I didn't go in there, but I...
So I guess it was Vern Scott that really kicked it off for me.
And then... Well, I think that was the main...
So when you got your degree, what happened to you then?
You didn't go in private?
I was going to Cleveland, a little town on the other side of Wake.
Close to Crankville, yeah.
And it was a pretty good dairy shed.
Well I had a Dairy Science B.S.
Degree in D.V.M.
and what I planned to do was become a dairy practitioner, dairy cattle, and concentrate on dairy cattle.
Going to little places like that you couldn't, you had to be somewhat of a generalist.
because there's nobody else there to concentrate on.
Well, long in the fourth year before we graduated, when I came back here and started veterinary medicine,
I got a job as an instructor in the Department of Veterinary Physiology, and I was teaching in Veterinary Physiology.
So I'd had Army experience and had taught in the Army, trained soldiers, and then the experience there in the Department of Veterinary Physiology.
Then I was about to graduate with a Ph.D. degree.
And Dr. John Miller, who was head of the Department of Anatomy, in the laboratory one day, histology laboratory, he came to my side and said, Price, have you ever thought about teaching?
I said, no.
He said, what are you going to do?
I said, I'm going to shift.
I'm going to Clifton, Texas.
I'm going to Clifton, Texas and practice bear catching.
He said, well, why don't you think about it?
And that's all he said.
I don't know what he wants.
He still wouldn't buy it.
And he asked me again about the possibility of going into teaching.
I said, no, I don't know.
Practice bear catching is what he intended the whole time.
And he didn't argue with me or anything.
But he came back the third time.
And I thought, well, I'm wrong.
Maybe it was telling him something.
And finally he said on that third time, he said, I've got a job for you if you pay me.
And I said, well, I'm going to come home and think about it and talk to my wife about it.
I'll be back for you.
Then I thought about it and thought, well, you know, I'm going to do it for a living.
And then I can still go to Texas for the market.
So I came back and told him, OK. And he said, well, that's fine.
Then you got the job.
I said, OK.
So graduated, summer was out, fall came.
Sessions?
What was the book?
Sessions?
Yeah.
Yeah, I remember that title.
That's why I'm asking.
I've got the old edition.
It's Sisson.
Sisson, is it?
Yeah.
S-I-S-S-O-N.
It's Sisson and Grossman.
I remember some of those old titles.
Sisson and Grossman.
Excuse me.
Go ahead.
That's something else I'd kind of like to ask you about, is the textbook and teaching side of it sometimes.
Well, he handed me that book, and of course I had been through the book and had me in school.
That textbook we used.
And he handed me the book and said, that's what you're going to teach.
And that's all the instructions I had.
So I started teaching.
And never left.
And obviously you enjoyed it.
What would have been the, what was your salary, starting salary, do you remember?
$3,200 a year.
I always remember my starting salary, too.
I have every payday in my drawer right there.
Yeah.
What would have been the situation had you gone into practice in Clifton?
Well, of course, Clifton no longer is a dairy share.
So something else would have had to happen.
And what would have happened, I have no idea.
What kind of an income or living would you have made had you gone into practice in Clifton at that time?
I'd had to starve for about three years.
Yeah, that was a pretty standard procedure when it'd be tough to get into the business.
Absolutely.

Now, when a practitioner like that went out into business on their own, basically you hang a shingle up and you're on your own, is it a matter of good public relations, a matter of someone being available?
What makes it work or not work?
Mostly public relations.
Public relations.
You've got to do a good job.
Yeah, sure.
Technical work.
Yeah.
That's true, but
People have to want to come to you.
They've got to like you.
I don't care if you're good at your technology.
People will like you.
They're not going to come to you.
And that's what some veterinarians miss.
You've got to satisfy them.
And sometimes you've got to do some things that you don't think was best, but they thought was best.
Now, when a veterinarian went out into practice then and now, I guess, this is a little bit broad,
I've been kind of interested in, was there or is there any business training for that veterinary?
Very little.
And still today, much too little.

The main thing that I've heard through the years, being here at the College of Veterinary Medicine, of people who left here, gone to here, and then feeding information back as to what they needed most during that first five years of the practice was some business
I'm wondering about that because, you know, just in that TVMA meeting the other day, it came immediately clear to me these people are basically businessmen, it seemed to me.
I mean, they're technicians, too.
They're doctors.
But they're running businesses, and those businesses, some of them apparently were big operations.
I know I was talking to...
His name took pinky in El Paso.
I'm sorry, but anyway.
Yeah, I know.
And I gathered he's done a lot of operating as a businessman as much as anybody else.
Sure, yes.
And a lot of these people have.
You run in the business.
That's correct.
So that was just one aspect that I was sort of intrigued about.
Well, in the period of time,
to get the technology in, there is just not enough time to make a businessman.
Of course, medical doctors have the same situation.
Yeah, that's correct.
Now, they will learn it the hard way.
If you give them the business without the technology, they can't learn that the hard way.
So you've got to give them the technology, the arts and skills of the practice of living medicine.
And then they will learn.
On their own, the business, it'll finally, for most of them, they'll melt.
Now, there are some that can, and they fade from the scene.
When they go out of here, now or in 1949, did you have any idea what kind of charges you should make for services and anything like that?
Yeah, we talked about that a little bit in school.
And we also had the practitioners
private clinical practitioners who would come and talk with us in a seminar or talk to the class about their experiences.
And that was good education.
They donated their time.
And we'd ask them questions.
What do you charge for so-and-so?
They'd get a pretty good idea.
On the other hand, even then, and I guess even more after that,
graduates were encouraged not to go directly into your private clinical practice.
Go to work for a veterinarian.
Observe what it is out there in the real world.
This veterinary hospital here is great, but it doesn't teach you the business end of that, nor the public relations end of that, the personal end of that.
And you learn that by just observing out there and working with a veterinarian.
Number one is,
If you go out there and you make a blunder in your practice, people are not going to come back to you.
You go out there and make a blunder in his practice, and he's already rooted.
And they'll come back to him.
So you learn from him and do your mistakes at his expense rather than your own.
Well, you say that apprenticeship is more common now than it was, say, earlier today.
Yeah.
do most of your students now going out of here actually go into some sort of apprenticeship situation?
I guess, if nothing else, having the capital to go into business would be a pretty big outlier.
Well, of course it was.
So I know a lot of our years have known a lot of vet students.
Many of them get into veterinary medicine because they like animals.
And yet one of the things you're telling me is that maybe the most important thing is that they like people.
Well, if they don't like people, it doesn't matter to them.
They just eat the people.
Yeah, sure.
Do you screen, or in the interview process that you go through, do you try, I mean, for their own good, I would assume.
Has that always happened?
Did that happen in 1949?
Well, I don't know of 1949.
I wasn't on the admission agenda.
I don't know, but we've tried through the years to build that in.
It's hard to build and it's subjective as it can be, but yeah, I'd make an effort to.
That's a good question.
How would you describe or profile a typical veterinarian or a student or someone that you think should be in that kind of business?
Do you have an image of a veterinarian?
I have an image of what a veterinarian ought to be.
What is that?
Yes.
And my image may be false.
I'm sure.
It may be false.
Number one, he's got to be accurate.
Accuracy of the technology, the skill, the art.
And you know, we've lost a great part of the art.
Dr. A.
A. Leonard, who used to be the head of the clinics, was an artist.
He could go out there and look at an animal and say, he's got so-and-so.
He didn't have to test.
I don't mean he didn't have to test, but...
had the visual capability of perceiving what that was.
And that's an art.
That's not a skill.
That's an art.
You work on that.
Today, we have tests, tests, tests, tests, tests, you see.
And there's nothing wrong with tests.
But we are losing the art of the practice of .
I don't want to put words in your mouth.
Getting into more skills.
So it's more technology-oriented than...
Absolutely.
Well, we didn't have the technology.
So we had to do the art.
And, you know, when I say art and skills, I guess art is a skill, too, but... No, I don't understand.
The intuition to say, that's that.

Well, I know that, for instance, way back there in the 1930's, Byrne Scott came to our place, and Daddy called him, and he came, and Daddy had a cow in the corral, and she wasn't doing anything with it, although Daddy obviously knew she was ill.
Dr. Bernard Scott looked over the fence and said, yeah.
Says she has hardware disease.
I said, what's hardware disease?
He says it's traumatic pericarditis.
That's important.
You know?
Cleared that right out.
Well, sure enough, she did.
There were certain signs and symptoms that that animal displayed that he had seen so many times that he knew what that was.
He didn't have to go any further.
Now, that is skill, but it's also art.
And we have lost a lot of that.
You know, the old cow, he's ticked.
She's got metal in her, pericardium in her heart.
She swallows a nail or a wire or something.
It goes into the stomach, into the rumen.
The rumen sits just behind the diaphragm, and the heart's over on this side beating.
And you try to put a hammer on the handle by hitting one end.
So literally, that's what's happening.
And the little heart's sitting there beating.
It just draws that thing right through the...
diaphragm and into the pericardium, the covering of the heart.
And all kinds of organisms in the room go in there, and she has an inflammation, an infection in the pericardium.
Traumatic.
It was traumatic pericarditis.
So a veterinarian is someone who is technically skilled in the factory.
Yeah.
At this day and time, he has to have the technology to compete.
You can't do it without the techniques and the implements and the gadgetry that you've developed.
To tell you the thing, one of the biggest things today is non-invasive techniques, sonar, OS, so that you can see what's inside without
invading the body from the invasive.
And that's a great problem.
Because any time you invade the body, the flesh, you cause a potential problem of infection and this sort of thing.
So you can see what's in there without doing that.
You're way ahead of the game.
So we're getting better and better and better with the technology, and it's going to get better and better, and the skills are going to be less and less.
And when I say skills and arts, they're going to continue to subside.
And I'm not saying that's wrong at all.
So you've got to have the technology this day and time.
It used to have to be the arts and the skills, and now the technology.
Now the second thing the guy's got to have is public relations.
He's got to like people.
He's got to know people and relate to people.
We have so many little girls coming.
A girl, a woman, a young woman comes to get her medicine because they fell in love with a horse.
But you've got to have more than that.
Some of them will say, well, I just love animals.
Shoot, you wouldn't want a veterinarian if you didn't love animals.
But that's just the beginning of it.
So that is an innate part of veterinary medicine is an affection, let's say, for animals.
Oh, yeah.
You have to have compassion for the welfare of the animal.
But on the other hand, we can't overlook the needs of the client.
You're working for a client, not for an animal.
And you've got to face those two also.
There are times when you can't do what you want to do.
Well, for one reason, it's too expensive.
And you know that you could make that animal better, maybe heal, if you could do what you really wanted to do.
But you can't afford to do it because it would cost more than that animal is worth.
you know, we don't have that problem.
You do it.
And insurance covers it or something.

On that same line, I don't know if this is the right place to do it because we need to get back to the profile of a veterinarian, but as I see it too, one of the difficulties in promoting or advancing the practice of veterinary medicine has been the problem of cost.
So, for example,
In fact, I was raised with the idea that animals are basically expendable, that you don't spend money on them.
I never spent a nickel on a pet.
They were always free, and if they died, tough.
You don't do that.
I spent a lot.
That's an old agrarian philosophy, though.
That's right, but I spend a lot of money on my dogs now.
Yeah, well, we've got to end the round, too, the human.
animal barn today, you know.
Yeah, and your high-priced equipment you're talking about is expensive stuff.
Absolutely.
So has part of the problem of veterinary medicine, you think, been convincing people that they need to invest in their animals?
I'm not sure if I'm asking that question correctly, but that somehow or other, in other words, you can prove the efficiencies, the cost efficiencies of taking care of animals.
Is that part of the
of the message that veterinarians have had to get across in the Southwest?
Well, you know, you can sort of classify people in two categories in that regard.
Those who have compassion for and will go all out for their animal.
And those who say, well, it's just a dog.
And there's a vast difference in that.
This one over here will pay the price.
No way.
Yeah.

Now, you know, they meld together in here, and they're not two extremes, but nevertheless, you have to know, as a veterinarian, as a private clinic practitioner, they have to know that this individual wants this dog fixed, no matter the cost.
This one over here, no, he just wants to know, should have killed him.
And you've got all that in there, and you've got to weasel that out of the people of your clients.
Your dog can't tell you that.
And you don't know that, so you've got to get it from within.
That's where the human relationship has to come in, to know what that client wants done.
That's really an intriguing and key point.
And if you please that client, you've got a regular client.
If you displease that client,
and going somewhere else.
And that's the way you build your business, is people relationship, not animals.
Has that changed over the years?
I mean, when you were growing up in Erath County, I imagine all your neighbors were farmers, agriculturists.
Animals were a means of production.
They were pets.
